{
  "doc_id": "55677",
  "text": "The recent development of new click-compatible sugar analogues-glucose, galactose, fucose, arabinose, rhamnose, and sucrose [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] -allows a good opportunity to develop this technique and to improve our knowledge on polysaccharide biosynthesis and function as soon as the current limitations of the method can be bypassed. In fact, click chemistry relies on the reaction of azides and/or alkynes and uses copper as a catalyst; thus, it does not allow dynamic imaging of living cells as copper is toxic for cells. Hopefully, alternative methods, termed \"copper-free click chemistry\", are currently being developed and have been successfully used to detect sugar analogues in living organisms using cyclooctyne ( Figure 12B ). For instance, the difluorinated cyclooctyne (DIFO) possesses ring strain and electron-withdrawing fluorine substituents that together promote dipolar cycloaddition with azides without the use of copper. The kinetics of the reaction are comparable to those of the copper-catalyzed reaction and it proceeds within minutes on living cells with no apparent toxicity. This method has been successfully used to label glycan in Chinese Hamster Ovary (CHO) cells [CITATION_3] in mouse [CITATION_4] and in plant [CITATION_5] with no apparent toxicity, and allows us to consider new promising and attractive applications for direct imaging of glycan in living cells. possesses ring strain and electron-withdrawing fluorine substituents that together promote dipolar cycloaddition with azides without the use of copper. The kinetics of the reaction are comparable to those of the copper-catalyzed reaction and it proceeds within minutes on living cells with no apparent toxicity. This method has been successfully used to label glycan in Chinese Hamster Ovary (CHO) cells [CITATION_6] in mouse [CITATION_7] and in plant [CITATION_8] with no apparent toxicity, and allows us to consider new promising and attractive applications for direct imaging of glycan in living cells. ",
